\begin_layout Standard
The operation +1 goes forward by one step in this table, and wraps around
 from the end to the start.
 The operation -1 goes in reverse.
 If we start with the value 0000 and subtract 1, we end up with 1111.
 For signed values that bit pattern indeed represents -1.
 If we keep subtracing -1's, it goes back to -8, which is the minimum representa
ble signed integer, and then wraps around to +7.
 You see that the operations +1 and -1 work exactly the same on a bit pattern,
 regardless of whether it represents a signed or unsigned value.
 The only difference is the meaning of the bit patterns: 1111 represents
 15 if it's an unsigned value, and -1 if it's a signed value.
 So if we 
\emph on
print
\emph default
 an integer, we need to know whether it's signed or unsigned, but as long
 as we only do +1 and -1 we don't need to know whether it's signed or unsigned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adding bigger amounts, say, +3, is independent of whether it's signed or
 unsigned too, because adding +5 is the same as +1+1+1, so if adding +1
 is independent of whether it's signed or unsigned, then +3 is too.
 Try an example: if we start with 1001 and add +2 we end up with 1011.
 As an unsigned value, that was 9+2=11, and with a signed value, that was
 -7+2=-5.
 Both correct! Similarly, subtracting bigger amounts, or adding negative
 amounts, also works.
 Multiplication be expressed as repeated addition, so that's independent
 too.
 This does 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 work for division, because division cannot be expressed as repeated addition
 of +1.
 That's why x86 has separate DIV and IDIV instructions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Technically, that argument only shows that addition 
\begin_inset Formula $a+b$
\end_inset

, subtraction 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b$
\end_inset

, and multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $a\cdot b$
\end_inset

 is independent of whether 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is signed or unsigned.
 You'll probably not be suprised that it's also independent of whether 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is signed or unsigned.
 If you're familiar with modular arithmetic, this is because 
\begin_inset Formula $(a\mod16)+(b\mod16)=(a+b)\mod16$
\end_inset

 and similarly for subtraction and multiplication.
 The only difference between signed and unsigned is which representative
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 we assign to each equivalence class in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/16\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 That's just a fancy way of saying that when we print a bit pattern, what
 we print depends on whether it represents a signed or unsigned value.
\end_layout

